51
00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:08.240
So as mentioned by Martha, I'll begin with an overview

52
00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:13.280
of pediatric extrapolation and its use in oncology drug development.

53
00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:20.440
So starting with the very basics, what exactly is pediatric

54
00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:21.230
extrapolation?

55
00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:25.240
So pediatric extrapolation is an approach to providing

56
00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:29.000
evidence in support of effective and safe use of drugs in the

57
00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:32.760
pediatric population when it can be assumed that the

58
00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:36.620
course of the disease and the expected response to a medicinal product

59
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.740
would be sufficiently similar in a pediatric and reference population.

60
00:03:41.980 --> 00:03:45.900
Notably, that reference population can be adults, but it can also include

61
00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:48.060
different pediatric age subsets.

62
00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:51.880
So for example, using data from adolescent patients to support a

63
00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:54.260
pediatric extrapolation to younger children.

64
00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:59.320
In general, the use of pediatric extrapolation helps to support

65
00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:02.480
safe, efficient, and ethical pediatric drug development.

66
00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:10.900
So as we all know, there are many challenges in the development of new

67
00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:12.900
drugs for pediatric patients with cancer.

68
00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.519
A few select challenges are shown here, including those related

69
00:04:17.601 --> 00:04:20.930
to ethics, feasibility, and late and long-term effects.

70
00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:25.480
Generally speaking, enrolling pediatric patients in a clinical

71
00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:29.210
trial evaluating an investigational drug intended to treat that

72
00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:32.920
patient's cancer would typically be considered acceptable with

73
00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:35.880
appropriate safety monitoring and dosing considerations.

74
00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:40.980
However, feasibility issues can result in very long

75
00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:44.700
timelines for enrollment and completion of trials in pediatric

76
00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:48.180
populations. In addition, those late and long-term

77
00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:51.540
toxicities may impact pediatric patients potentially for up to

78
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.560
decades during and after their treatment, which may require long

79
00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:59.230
durations of follow-up. Given these many challenges and

80
00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:03.060
others for developing drugs in pediatric patients, pediatric

81
00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:07.040
extrapolation represents an important tool in supporting efficient

82
00:05:07.060 --> 00:05:07.820
drug development.

83
00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:17.620
While the use of pediatric extrapolation in

84
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:21.420
oncology does appear to be increasing, the concept of pediatric

85
00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:25.350
extrapolation is not new and in fact has been in US regulation

86
00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:28.920
for more than 30 years. In 1994, the

87
00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:30.180
pediatric labeling rule

88
00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:35.260
described acceptability of pediatric extrapolation to

89
00:05:35.300 --> 00:05:38.950
support pediatric use statements in labeling and specified that

90
00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:42.660
pharmacokinetic or PK data and pediatric safety information be

91
00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:43.760
submitted where needed.

92
00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:48.550
Thirty years later, in 2024, the International Council for

93
00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:52.300
Harmonisation, or ICH, published a final guideline on

94
00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:56.200
pediatric extrapolation. This guideline provides consensus

95
00:05:56.280 --> 00:06:00.140
recommendations for pediatric extrapolation, which I will cover in more

96
00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:03.484
detail in the next few slides.One notable

97
00:06:03.494 --> 00:06:07.144
difference from previous guidance on pediatric extrapolation is the

98
00:06:07.204 --> 00:06:10.994
explicit allowance for extrapolation of safety where supported by

99
00:06:11.044 --> 00:06:11.664
available data.

100
00:06:14.644 --> 00:06:18.144
Within FDA oncology, we regularly see applications of pediatric

101
00:06:18.204 --> 00:06:22.124
extrapolation, and a recent FDA evaluation found that more

102
00:06:22.144 --> 00:06:26.104
than half of all new pediatric oncology indications approved

103
00:06:26.124 --> 00:06:29.674
between 2013 and 2024 utilized pediatric

104
00:06:29.724 --> 00:06:31.924
extrapolation in some way to support that approval.

105
00:06:33.484 --> 00:06:36.244
As mentioned, we'll be discussing a few select examples throughout the

106
00:06:36.264 --> 00:06:39.434
presentations today, but there are many more examples,

107
00:06:40.224 --> 00:06:43.264
either that are already approved or are currently in development.

108
00:06:46.364 --> 00:06:50.124
So now moving more into the actual process for conducting a pediatric

109
00:06:50.164 --> 00:06:51.784
extrapolation approach.

110
00:06:52.824 --> 00:06:56.504
This slide highlights the pediatric extrapolation framework that's

111
00:06:56.564 --> 00:06:58.924
described in the ICH E11A guideline.

112
00:06:59.704 --> 00:07:03.524
There are three main steps for pediatric extrapolation.

113
00:07:03.544 --> 00:07:06.384
First, developing the pediatric extrapolation concept.

114
00:07:07.444 --> 00:07:09.644
Second, creating the pediatric extrapolation plan.

115
00:07:10.374 --> 00:07:11.824
And finally, executing that plan.

116
00:07:13.204 --> 00:07:17.064
To develop the concept, developers must integrate available evidence

117
00:07:17.124 --> 00:07:21.044
on disease, drug pharmacology, and response to treatment and

118
00:07:21.104 --> 00:07:23.544
safety in the reference and target populations.

119
00:07:24.214 --> 00:07:27.444
This includes assessments of the strength of evidence, the

120
00:07:27.464 --> 00:07:31.254
uncertainties, and knowledge gaps that need to be addressed during development.

121
00:07:32.884 --> 00:07:36.574
Once the concept has been developed, the objectives of the pediatric

122
00:07:36.624 --> 00:07:40.364
extrapolation plan can be defined to address uncertainties and knowledge

123
00:07:40.444 --> 00:07:40.734
gaps.

124
00:07:41.804 --> 00:07:45.474
These can include plans to determine PK, dosing, efficacy,

125
00:07:46.004 --> 00:07:48.204
safety as needed based on the knowledge gaps.

126
00:07:49.574 --> 00:07:53.244
And then finally, executing the plan by conducting the needed studies to generate

127
00:07:53.264 --> 00:07:53.564
data.

128
00:07:54.524 --> 00:07:57.874
Importantly, these plans should be iterated based on the emerging data,

129
00:07:59.084 --> 00:08:02.064
which can come from within the studies conducted as part of the pediatric

130
00:08:02.124 --> 00:08:05.864
extrapolation plan, but can also include other sources, for example,

131
00:08:05.964 --> 00:08:07.004
newly published literature.

132
00:08:08.464 --> 00:08:11.924
Given the iterative nature of a pediatric extrapolation plan,

133
00:08:12.604 --> 00:08:16.584
FDA strongly encourages sponsors to initiate the framework early in

134
00:08:16.624 --> 00:08:19.944
their drug development plans, particularly when there is obvious

135
00:08:20.004 --> 00:08:22.734
applicability to one or more pediatric cancers,

136
00:08:23.593 --> 00:08:26.154
and to engage with FDA on these plans throughout development.

137
00:08:27.093 --> 00:08:30.794
These discussions can occur as part of other regular milestone meetings,

138
00:08:31.404 --> 00:08:35.384
but can also occur via a specific pediatric oncology

139
00:08:35.465 --> 00:08:37.284
product development early advice meeting.

140
00:08:41.444 --> 00:08:45.194
This slide summarizes a little more detail on the assessment of similarity and

141
00:08:45.244 --> 00:08:48.644
approaches for pediatric extrapolation as outlined in the ICH

142
00:08:48.684 --> 00:08:49.264
E11A.

143
00:08:50.624 --> 00:08:54.224
The extrapolation approaches and potential study designs depend on a

144
00:08:54.284 --> 00:08:56.484
continuum

145
00:08:57.924 --> 00:09:01.884
of the level of evidence and confidence level in similarity of disease, drug

146
00:09:01.944 --> 00:09:05.644
pharmacology, and response to treatment between a pediatric and reference

147
00:09:05.664 --> 00:09:06.274
population.

148
00:09:07.154 --> 00:09:10.904
A wide variety of data sources and types are evaluated to

149
00:09:10.924 --> 00:09:13.984
support conclusions and identify gaps or uncertainties.

150
00:09:15.044 --> 00:09:18.584
Since this is a continuum, the evaluation of similarity is not

151
00:09:18.644 --> 00:09:22.144
intended to be a binary determination of whether the

152
00:09:22.184 --> 00:09:26.104
disease or response in the reference in pediatric populations is exactly

153
00:09:26.144 --> 00:09:29.924
the same or not, but rather to determine the degree of similarity or

154
00:09:29.944 --> 00:09:30.684
dissimilarity.

155
00:09:32.164 --> 00:09:35.914
This framework also helps to highlight that even in scenarios where

156
00:09:35.924 --> 00:09:39.524
pediatric and adult cancers and response to treatment are expected to be

157
00:09:39.584 --> 00:09:43.364
highly similar, we need high quality data to support a pediatric

158
00:09:43.434 --> 00:09:44.144
development plan.

159
00:09:46.244 --> 00:09:50.004
Now, looking at potential study designs, the types of data and designs of

160
00:09:50.064 --> 00:09:53.804
studies proposed in a pediatric extrapolation plan can range from

161
00:09:53.813 --> 00:09:57.784
exposure matching and enrollment in adult trials to randomized

162
00:09:57.924 --> 00:10:01.584
trials conducted specifically in the relevant pediatric

163
00:10:01.604 --> 00:10:02.184
population.

164
00:10:04.044 --> 00:10:07.864
The specific study types needed will depend on the knowledge gaps and

165
00:10:07.873 --> 00:10:11.524
degree of similarity between the pediatric population and the reference population.

166
00:10:18.744 --> 00:10:21.924
It's not going. Okay, there we go. Sorry, it wouldn't connect.

167
00:10:23.163 --> 00:10:26.624
So this slide provides just a little more detail on some specific considerations

168
00:10:27.324 --> 00:10:29.524
when developing a pediatric extrapolation plan.

169
00:10:30.564 --> 00:10:33.904
While not all elements will be applicable to all programs,

170
00:10:34.404 --> 00:10:38.064
developers should generally consider things such as including adolescents in adult

171
00:10:38.074 --> 00:10:39.384
trials where appropriate,

172
00:10:40.424 --> 00:10:44.184
leveraging of modeling and simulation approaches, which will be discussed in more

173
00:10:44.284 --> 00:10:46.324
detail by our next presenter.

174
00:10:47.394 --> 00:10:51.244
These model-informed drug development or MIDD approaches can help us with

175
00:10:51.284 --> 00:10:55.084
data leveraging to bridge knowledge gaps, inform clinical trial design

176
00:10:55.184 --> 00:10:58.884
elements, and identify appropriate dosages for evaluation across

177
00:10:58.924 --> 00:10:59.984
pediatric age ranges.

178
00:11:01.564 --> 00:11:05.164
In addition, age-appropriate formulation development, including both the needed

179
00:11:05.264 --> 00:11:09.144
characteristics of an age-appropriate formulation as well as the timeline

180
00:11:09.184 --> 00:11:11.404
for development of that formulation should be considered.

181
00:11:12.764 --> 00:11:16.044
Dosage selection and the use of dose ranging data and biomarkers.

182
00:11:16.924 --> 00:11:20.904
Other relationships can be established to endpoints between a reference and target

183
00:11:20.924 --> 00:11:24.144
population. And finally, a safety extrapolation plan,

184
00:11:24.584 --> 00:11:28.544
including areas where safety extrapolation may not be sufficient, such

185
00:11:28.584 --> 00:11:31.264
as age-specific toxicities.

186
00:11:34.164 --> 00:11:37.324
So before I wrap up, I'm going to briefly use the initial approval of

187
00:11:37.384 --> 00:11:41.044
selpercatinib as an example of some of these pediatric

188
00:11:41.084 --> 00:11:43.624
extrapolation at MIDD considerations.

189
00:11:44.874 --> 00:11:48.694
Selpercatinib is a small molecule RET inhibitor that was initially approved in

190
00:11:48.724 --> 00:11:51.074
May 2020 for multiple indications.

191
00:11:51.824 --> 00:11:55.574
Two of those approved indications included adolescent patients at the

192
00:11:55.664 --> 00:11:57.924
time of initial approval, as shown here,

193
00:11:58.744 --> 00:12:02.304
for both RET mutant medullary thyroid cancer and RET fusion

194
00:12:02.504 --> 00:12:06.112
positive thyroid cancersThe

195
00:12:06.172 --> 00:12:09.952
approval of adolescent patients at the time of the initial approval was

196
00:12:09.972 --> 00:12:13.692
supported by a pediatric extrapolation approach that included the following

197
00:12:13.712 --> 00:12:14.592
considerations.

198
00:12:15.592 --> 00:12:19.292
First, a combination of clinical and non-clinical data supported

199
00:12:19.472 --> 00:12:23.082
high confidence in similarity of disease, drug pharmacology, and

200
00:12:23.092 --> 00:12:26.452
response to treatment for both of the thyroid cancer

201
00:12:26.492 --> 00:12:27.092
indications.

202
00:12:28.292 --> 00:12:32.152
In addition, adolescent patients were eligible for the first inhuman

203
00:12:32.172 --> 00:12:34.752
dose escalation and expansion trial of selpercatinib.

204
00:12:35.722 --> 00:12:39.412
While ultimately few adolescent patients enrolled, given the rarity of disease,

205
00:12:40.082 --> 00:12:43.832
the eligibility did result in availability of PK safety and activity

206
00:12:43.872 --> 00:12:45.772
data from relevant adolescent patients.

207
00:12:47.312 --> 00:12:51.272
Next, modeling and simulation was leveraged using additional

208
00:12:51.292 --> 00:12:54.812
PK and safety data from lower body weight adults across a range of

209
00:12:54.852 --> 00:12:58.032
dosages to support a recommended body weight-based dosing

210
00:12:58.092 --> 00:13:01.872
strategy that would accommodate the expected range of body weights in

211
00:13:01.932 --> 00:13:02.882
adolescent patients.

212
00:13:04.102 --> 00:13:07.962
And finally, non-clinical data identified a potential pediatric

213
00:13:08.092 --> 00:13:11.652
specific safety concern for patients whose growth plates had not yet

214
00:13:11.692 --> 00:13:12.092
closed.

215
00:13:12.902 --> 00:13:16.772
This pediatric specific safety concern led to the issuance of a

216
00:13:16.812 --> 00:13:18.452
pediatric safety PMR

217
00:13:19.832 --> 00:13:22.632
to monitor growth and development in pediatric patients.

218
00:13:23.712 --> 00:13:27.292
Ultimately, the totality of data available from the pediatric extrapolation

219
00:13:27.312 --> 00:13:30.832
approach allowed FDA to approve selpercatinib in adolescent

220
00:13:30.912 --> 00:13:33.772
patients with no time delay from the initial approval in adults.

221
00:13:35.032 --> 00:13:38.472
Notably, additional data were later collected as part of the iterative

222
00:13:38.612 --> 00:13:40.192
pediatric extrapolation plan,

223
00:13:41.092 --> 00:13:44.612
which led to expansion to even younger patients, now as young as age two.

224
00:13:48.812 --> 00:13:51.592
So now before our next speaker, just a few quick take home messages.

225
00:13:52.112 --> 00:13:55.572
Pediatric extrapolation supports safe, efficient and ethical

226
00:13:55.712 --> 00:13:57.472
pediatric oncology drug development.

227
00:13:58.472 --> 00:14:01.892
Pediatric extrapolation plans can leverage tools, including

228
00:14:02.032 --> 00:14:05.852
MIDD to bridge knowledge gaps and inform pediatric trial designs.

229
00:14:06.912 --> 00:14:10.692
Developers should consider pediatric extrapolation plans early in drug

230
00:14:10.702 --> 00:14:13.472
development and update those plans as data emerge.

231
00:14:14.632 --> 00:14:18.521
And finally, FDA is open for engagement and advice on pediatric

232
00:14:18.572 --> 00:14:20.752
extrapolation plans throughout drug development.

233
00:14:22.972 --> 00:14:25.772
I'd like to acknowledge the many people who contribute to this work.

234
00:14:26.372 --> 00:14:28.972
And now I will hand it off to our next speaker, Jiang Liu.

235
00:14:44.932 --> 00:14:48.732
Good afternoon. So it's such a great pleasure to be

236
00:14:48.792 --> 00:14:49.032
here.

237
00:14:50.052 --> 00:14:53.282
I'm Jiang Liu, currently the Deputy Division Director of

238
00:14:53.392 --> 00:14:57.032
Pharmacometrics or Quantitative Clinical Pharmacology.

239
00:14:57.832 --> 00:15:01.622
So here I will discuss how model informed drug development or

240
00:15:01.732 --> 00:15:05.512
MIDD can support drug extrapolation for pediatric

241
00:15:05.552 --> 00:15:06.432
cancer patients.

242
00:15:09.232 --> 00:15:13.012
So following Lauren's introduction to extrapolation for

243
00:15:13.292 --> 00:15:17.152
pediatric cancer patients, I will focus on the methodological

244
00:15:17.292 --> 00:15:21.152
aspects, particularly how MIDD supports pediatric

245
00:15:21.292 --> 00:15:24.792
extrapolation through the following three key areas:

246
00:15:25.592 --> 00:15:29.312
leveraging existing data and knowledge to bridge

247
00:15:29.552 --> 00:15:30.412
evidence gaps

248
00:15:31.252 --> 00:15:35.132
and inform trial design and optimizing

249
00:15:35.172 --> 00:15:38.452
dose selection. I will also introduce some case

250
00:15:38.572 --> 00:15:41.312
examples, followed by key takeaways.

251
00:15:43.612 --> 00:15:47.052
So, as Lauren introduced, under SHE 11,

252
00:15:47.632 --> 00:15:51.312
pediatric extrapolation means borrowing existing evidence,

253
00:15:51.912 --> 00:15:55.452
most often evidence of drug effectiveness, but sometimes

254
00:15:55.552 --> 00:15:59.452
